model solution output:
## Main Idea

The problem asks us to find an integer time $t \in [0, K]$ that maximizes the maximum flow from the power supply at $(1, 1)$ to the city hall at $(N, M)$. Each block $(i, j)$ acts as a vertex with a time-varying capacity $C_{ij} + t \cdot R_{ij}$.

By the max-flow min-cut theorem, the maximum flow equals the capacity of the minimum vertex cut. Since the capacity of each vertex is a linear function of $t$, the total capacity of any cut $W$ is also a linear function of $t$: $C(W) + t \cdot R(W)$. The maximum flow function $f(t)$ is the pointwise minimum over all valid cuts:


$$f(t) = \min_{W} (C(W) + t \cdot R(W))$$


Because it is the pointwise minimum of linear functions, $f(t)$ is a concave function of $t$. To find its maximum over the integer range $[0, K]$, we can use a slope-based search.

When we compute the maximum flow at a specific time $t$, we can identify a minimum cut $W$ by finding all vertices reachable from the source in the residual graph. The slope of this cut is given by $R(W) = \sum_{v \in W} R_v$. By concavity:

* If $R(W) > 0$, the optimal time is guaranteed to be $\ge t$.
* If $R(W) < 0$, the optimal time is guaranteed to be $\le t$.
* If $R(W) = 0$, then $t$ is an optimal time.

We can accelerate the search by finding the intersection of the tangent lines at the boundaries of our active search interval $[L, R]$, falling back to standard binary search if needed.

## Complexity Analysis

* **Time Complexity:** - The flow network contains $V = 2NM$ vertices and $E = NM + 2P$ edges. Given $N, M \le 300$ and $P \le 2NM$, we have $V \le 180,000$ and $E \le 450,000$.
* In each step, we reset edge capacities in $O(V + E)$ time and execute Dinic's algorithm. For grid-like and planar graphs, Dinic's algorithm runs much faster than its theoretical worst-case bound, typically requiring very few blocking flow phases.
* The slope-based intersection method converges in a few iterations (typically $\le 10$), and the binary search fallback ensures at most $O(\log K)$ iterations. Thus, the total time complexity is $O(\log K \cdot \text{Dinic}(V, E))$, which easily fits well within the 6-second limit.


* **Memory Complexity:** - Storing the adjacency lists, level graphs, and backing structures requires $O(V + E)$ space. This takes a few megabytes, well within the 1024 MB limit.

## Complete C++ Implementation

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <vector>
#include <queue>
#include <algorithm>
#include <cmath>

using namespace std;

const long long INF = 2e18;

struct NetworkEdge {
    int to;
    int rev;
    long long cap;
};

int N, M, P;
long long K;
int total_nodes;
vector<vector<NetworkEdge>> adj;
vector<int> level;
vector<int> ptr;

struct BackingEdge {
    int u, idx;
    long long C, R;
};
vector<BackingEdge> forward_edges;
vector<long long> R_blocks;

void add_edge(int u, int v, long long cap) {
    adj[u].push_back({v, (int)adj[v].size(), cap});
    adj[v].push_back({u, (int)adj[u].size() - 1, 0});
}

void reset_network(long long t) {
    for (int u = 0; u < total_nodes; ++u) {
        for (auto& e : adj[u]) {
            e.cap = 0;
        }
    }
    for (auto& fe : forward_edges) {
        long long capacity = fe.C + t * fe.R;
        adj[fe.u][fe.idx].cap = capacity;
    }
}

bool bfs(int s, int t_sink) {
    fill(level.begin(), level.end(), -1);
    level[s] = 0;
    queue<int> q;
    q.push(s);
    while (!q.empty()) {
        int v = q.front();
        q.pop();
        for (auto& edge : adj[v]) {
            if (edge.cap > 0 && level[edge.to] == -1) {
                level[edge.to] = level[v] + 1;
                q.push(edge.to);
            }
        }
    }
    return level[t_sink] != -1;
}

long long dfs(int v, int t_sink, long long pushed) {
    if (pushed == 0) return 0;
    if (v == t_sink) return pushed;
    for (int& cid = ptr[v]; cid < adj[v].size(); ++cid) {
        auto& edge = adj[v][cid];
        int tr = edge.to;
        if (level[v] + 1 != level[tr] || edge.cap == 0) continue;
        long long tr_pushed = dfs(tr, t_sink, min(pushed, edge.cap));
        if (tr_pushed == 0) continue;
        edge.cap -= tr_pushed;
        adj[tr][edge.rev].cap += tr_pushed;
        return tr_pushed;
    }
    return 0;
}

