### Main idea

The problem asks us to find an 8-bit pattern $B$ and a sequence of shift operations that XOR to a target $N$-bit string $C$ using the minimum number of operations. Because the pattern is only 8 bits long, there are at most 255 non-zero candidates for $B$.

For a fixed pattern $B$, applying the operation at different shifts is equivalent to solving a linear system of equations over GF(2). Let $f$ and $l$ be the positions of the first and last 1-bits in $B$. The target string $C$ is formed by shifting $B$ such that its bits overlap with $C$. This establishes a linear recurrence relation where each bit of the operation sequence is uniquely determined by the previously chosen bits and the corresponding bit of $C$. Because the bit span of $B$ is $l - f + 1 \le 8$, there are exactly $K = l - f \le 7$ degrees of freedom (free variables) at the boundary. By brute-forcing the $2^K \le 128$ possible assignments for these boundary variables, we can simulate the linear recurrence in $O(N)$ time to deduce the remainder of the operations and count the total number of operations required. We do this for all possible patterns $B$ and record the global minimum.

### Technique used

**Linear Algebra over GF(2) / Exhaustive Search (Brute Force with Pruning)**
We exploit the bounded width of the pattern to frame the operation as a deterministic linear recurrence, allowing an exhaustive search over a very small state space of free variables for each candidate pattern.

### Correctness argument

Any application of pattern $B$ that overlaps with the target indices $[0, N-1]$ must begin at a shift between $-l$ and $N-1-f$. Operations outside this range modify bits strictly outside the interval $[0, N-1]$ without affecting the target sequence $C$, so an optimal solution will never use them.

Let $x_i \in \{0, 1\}$ represent whether pattern $B$ is applied at offset $i$. For any bit $k$ in $C$:
$c_k = \bigoplus_{j=f}^{l} x_{k-j} \cdot b_j$

Because $b_f = 1$ (by definition of the first 1-bit), we can rearrange the equation to isolate the highest-indexed variable:
$x_{k-f} = c_k \oplus \bigoplus_{j=f+1}^{l} x_{k-j} \cdot b_j$

This is a strict linear recurrence. If we simply guess the first $K = l - f$ active variables (which has at most $2^7$ possibilities), every subsequent $x_i$ is completely and uniquely dictated by $C$. Thus, for each $B$, iterating through the $2^K$ prefixes definitively explores all valid ways to generate $C$. The earliest $B$ that yields the minimum sum of $x_i$ directly breaks ties by the smallest base-2 integer value.

### Complexity analysis

* **Time Complexity:** For a given pattern $B$, let $K = l - f$. We evaluate $2^K$ initial states. Over all 255 patterns, the sum of all states is exactly $\sum_{K=0}^{7} (8-K) 2^{2K-1} = 14566$. For each state, computing the recurrence takes $O(N)$ time. The global time complexity is tightly bounded by $O(14566 \cdot N) = O(N)$. For $N = 4096$, the operations comfortably total $\approx 6 \times 10^7$, taking a fraction of a second and cleanly beating the 1.5s time limit.
* **Memory Complexity:** $O(N)$ auxiliary space is required to store the target sequence $C$ and the recurrent sequence array $x$, remaining extremely lightweight.

### Complete C++20 implementation

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <vector>
#include <string>

using namespace std;

int main() {
    ios_base::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(NULL);

    int N;
    if (!(cin >> N)) return 0;

    string s;
    cin >> s;

    bool all_zero = true;
    for (char ch : s) {
        if (ch == '1') {
            all_zero = false;
            break;
        }
    }

    if (all_zero) {
        cout << "00000000 0\n";
        return 0;
    }

    vector<int> c(N);
    for (int i = 0; i < N; ++i) {
        c[i] = s[i] - '0';
    }

    int min_Q = 1e9;
    int best_B = -1;
    vector<int> x(N + 8);

    for (int B = 1; B <= 255; ++B) {
        int b[8];
        for (int i = 0; i < 8; ++i) {
            b[i] = (B >> (7 - i)) & 1;
        }

        int f = 0, l = 7;
        while (b[f] == 0) f++;
        while (b[l] == 0) l--;

        int K = l - f;
        vector<int> active_j;
        for (int j = f + 1; j <= l; ++j) {
            if (b[j]) active_j.push_back(l - j);
        }

        int num_masks = 1 << K;
        for (int mask = 0; mask < num_masks; ++mask) {
            int cost = 0;
            for (int i = 0; i < K; ++i) {
                x[i] = (mask >> i) & 1;
                cost += x[i];
            }

            if (cost >= min_Q) continue;

            bool possible = true;
            for (int k = 0; k < N; ++k) {
                int val = c[k];
                for (int offset : active_j) {
                    val ^= x[k + offset];
                }
                x[k + K] = val;
                cost += val;
                if (cost >= min_Q) {
                    possible = false;
                    break;
                }
            }

            if (possible && cost < min_Q) {
                min_Q = cost;
                best_B = B;
            }
        }
    }

    for (int i = 0; i < 8; ++i) {
        cout << ((best_B >> (7 - i)) & 1);
    }
    cout << " " << min_Q << "\n";

    return 0;
}

