model solution output:
### Main idea

The problem asks for the minimum number of shuffling steps $k$ such that the initial deck $A$ becomes the target deck $B$ after applying the permutation $P$ exactly $k$ times. Since $P$ is a permutation, it can be decomposed into disjoint cycles.

For each cycle of length $L$, the permutation cyclically shifts the sequence of values at those positions by 1 position per step. Therefore, we can extract the sequence of values from $A$ and $B$ along each cycle. The target sequence $B_{cycle}$ must be a cyclic shift of $A_{cycle}$. We can use the Knuth-Morris-Pratt (KMP) algorithm to find the first occurrence of $A_{cycle}$ in $B_{cycle} + B_{cycle}$, which gives the smallest shift amount $m_c$. Furthermore, using KMP, we can find the smallest period $p_c$ of $A_{cycle}$.

For the cycle, the number of steps $k$ must satisfy the congruence $k \equiv m_c \pmod{p_c}$.
By breaking down $p_c$ into prime powers $p^e$, we can collect a set of congruences $k \equiv r \pmod{p^e}$ for all cycles. We merge congruences for the same prime to ensure there are no contradictions (if there are, we return `IMPOSSIVEL`). Finally, we solve the valid system of congruences using the Chinese Remainder Theorem (CRT). Because any valid $k > 10^9$ should trigger `DEMAIS`, we can cap our CRT modulus at $10^9$, circumventing the need for large number (BigInt) arithmetic.

### Technique used

* **Permutation Cycles:** To break the operation into independent cyclic shifts.
* **Knuth-Morris-Pratt (KMP):** To find the minimum shift $m_c$ and the sequence period $p_c$ in $O(L)$ time per cycle.
* **Number Theory & CRT:** To merge modular requirements from each prime power safely and efficiently.

### Correctness argument

A shuffle maps the item at $i$ to $P_i$. By tracking the values backward along a cycle, one shuffle equates to cyclically shifting the cycle's sequence rightward by 1. For each cycle, $B_{cycle}$ must be a valid rotation of $A_{cycle}$, establishing a requirement modulo the period $p_c$. Because cycles are independent, the global $k$ must satisfy the congruences $k \equiv m_c \pmod{p_c}$ simultaneously for all cycles.

By decomposing the periods into maximal prime powers, any contradictions (e.g., $k \equiv 1 \pmod 2$ and $k \equiv 0 \pmod 4$) are caught immediately. Once validated, CRT guarantees at least one non-negative solution exists. While calculating CRT, if the running modulus $M$ surpasses $10^9$, then any new answer $\ge M$ will be $> 10^9$. Hence, we can safely lock the candidate $K$ and just verify if it satisfies the remaining prime powers. If it doesn't, we can immediately conclude any true answer is $> 10^9$.

### Complexity analysis

* **Time Complexity:** $O(N)$. Identifying cycles takes $O(N)$ time. The KMP algorithm processes strings of total length $N$ across all cycles, taking $O(N)$ overall. Prime factorization and checking prime powers uses a precomputed sieve taking $O(N)$ to build, and factoring takes $O(\log N)$ per cycle. The CRT merge step operates strictly on the unique prime factors, capping operations well under $\approx 8 \times 10^4$.
* **Memory Complexity:** $O(N)$. Memory handles the original configurations arrays, cyclic extraction bounds, and sieve arrays safely falling into $\approx 25 \text{ MB}$, well below the generous 1024 MB restriction.

### Complete C++20 implementation

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <vector>

using namespace std;

const int MAXN = 1000000;
int min_prime[MAXN + 1];
int max_pow[MAXN + 1];
int rem_arr[MAXN + 1];

long long extGCD(long long a, long long b, long long &x, long long &y) {
    if (b == 0) {
        x = 1;
        y = 0;
        return a;
    }
    long long x1, y1;
    long long d = extGCD(b, a % b, x1, y1);
    x = y1;
    y = x1 - y1 * (a / b);
    return d;
}

long long modInverse(long long a, long long m) {
    long long x, y;
    extGCD(a, m, x, y);
    return (x % m + m) % m;
}

int main() {
    ios_base::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(NULL);

    for (int i = 2; i <= MAXN; i++) {
        min_prime[i] = i;
    }
    for (int i = 2; i * i <= MAXN; i++) {
        if (min_prime[i] == i) {
            for (int j = i * i; j <= MAXN; j += i) {
                if (min_prime[j] == j) {
                    min_prime[j] = i;
                }
            }
        }
    }

    int N;
    if (!(cin >> N)) return 0;

    vector<int> A(N), B(N), P(N);
    for (int i = 0; i < N; i++) cin >> A[i];
    for (int i = 0; i < N; i++) cin >> B[i];
    for (int i = 0; i < N; i++) {
        cin >> P[i];
        P[i]--;
    }

    vector<bool> visited(N, false);
    vector<int> used_primes;

    for (int i = 0; i < N; i++) {
        if (!visited[i]) {
            vector<int> cycle_nodes;
            int curr = i;
            while (!visited[curr]) {
                visited[curr] = true;
                cycle_nodes.push_back(curr);
                curr = P[curr];
            }

            vector<int> S_A, S_B;
            for (int node : cycle_nodes) {
                S_A.push_back(A[node]);
                S_B.push_back(B[node]);
            }

            int L = S_A.size();
            vector<int> pi(L, 0);
            int j = 0;
            for (int x = 1; x < L; x++) {
                while (j > 0 && S_A[x] != S_A[j]) {
                    j = pi[j - 1];
                }
                if (S_A[x] == S_A[j]) {
                    j++;
                }
                pi[x] = j;
            }

            int period = L;
            if (L % (L - pi[L - 1]) == 0) {
                period = L - pi[L - 1];
            }

            int match = -1;
            j = 0;
            for (int x = 0; x <= 2 * L - 2; x++) {
                int val = S_B[x % L];
                while (j > 0 && val != S_A[j]) {
                    j = pi[j - 1];
                }
                if (val == S_A[j]) {
                    j++;
                }
                if (j == L) {
                    match = x - L + 1;
                    break;
                }
            }

            if (match == -1) {
                cout << "IMPOSSIVEL\n";
                return 0;
            }

            int m_c = match % period;

            int temp = period;
            while (temp > 1) {
                int p = min_prime[temp];
                int q = 1;
                while (temp % p == 0) {
                    q *= p;
                    temp /= p;
                }
                int r = m_c % q;

                if (max_pow[p] == 0) {
                    max_pow[p] = q;
                    rem_arr[p] = r;
                    used_primes.push_back(p);
                } else {
                    int q_old = max_pow[p];
                    int r_old = rem_arr[p];
                    if (q_old >= q) {
                        if (r_old % q != r) {
                            cout << "IMPOSSIVEL\n";
                            return 0;
                        }
                    } else {
                        if (r % q_old != r_old) {
                            cout << "IMPOSSIVEL\n";
                            return 0;
                        }
                        max_pow[p] = q;
                        rem_arr[p] = r;
                    }
                }
            }
        }
    }

    long long K = 0;
    long long M = 1;
    bool M_large = false;

    for (int p : used_primes) {
        long long q = max_pow[p];
        long long r = rem_arr[p];

        if (!M_large) {
            long long diff = (r - K % q) % q;
            if (diff < 0) diff += q;

            if (diff > 0) {
                long long inv = modInverse(M % q, q);
                long long t = (diff * inv) % q;
                K = K + t * M;
                if (K > 1000000000LL) {
                    cout << "DEMAIS\n";
                    return 0;
                }
            }

            M = M * q;
            if (M > 1000000000LL) {
                M_large = true;
            }
        } else {
            if (K % q != r) {
                cout << "DEMAIS\n";
                return 0;
            }
        }
    }

    cout << K << "\n";
    return 0;
}

