model solution output:
### Main idea

The problem asks us to find a maximum subset of T-shirts such that no two selected models share the same text color or the same background color. We are given the incompatibility matrix $A$, where $A_{i,j}=1$ if two T-shirts share at least one color.

Notice that each T-shirt can be seen as an edge connecting a "text color" to a "background color" in a bipartite graph. The given matrix $A$ is precisely the line graph of this underlying bipartite graph. The problem translates to finding the Maximum Independent Set in the line graph, which is equivalent to finding the **Maximum Bipartite Matching** in the original bipartite graph.

To do this, we can uniquely reconstruct the vertices of the bipartite graph (the colors) by identifying all maximal cliques in the matrix $A$. Every vertex in the line graph belongs to at most two maximal cliques. After identifying the cliques and associating each T-shirt with its two endpoints (colors), we 2-color the reconstructed bipartite graph and run a standard maximum matching algorithm.

### Technique used

Graph Theory, Line Graph Reconstruction, and Bipartite Matching (Kuhn's Algorithm).

### Correctness argument

In a general graph, reconstructing the original graph from its line graph can be ambiguous. However, since the underlying graph is bipartite, it contains no cycles of length 3 (triangles). Consequently, any triangle in the line graph $A$ must originate from a "star" (multiple edges sharing the same vertex/color) in the bipartite graph.

Thus, two T-shirts $u$ and $v$ that share a color (meaning $A_{u,v} = 1$) will be part of a unique maximal clique comprising $u, v$, and every other T-shirt $x$ connected to **both** $u$ and $v$. By iterating through the unprocessed edges in $A$ and grouping common neighbors, we perfectly recover all stars of the original bipartite graph. These stars represent the unique text and background colors. Then, computing the maximum matching over this reconstructed bipartite graph ensures we pick the maximum number of edges such that no two share any endpoint.

### Complexity analysis

* **Time Complexity:** - **Clique Reconstruction:** The outer loops iterate through all pairs $O(N^2)$. The inner loop to find common neighbors runs in $O(N)$ time but is triggered *only once per maximal clique*. Since a line graph of a bipartite graph has at most $2N$ maximal cliques of size $\ge 2$, the total inner loop operations amount to $O(N \cdot 2N) = O(N^2)$.
* **Matching:** Kuhn’s algorithm runs in $O(|V| \cdot |E|)$, where $|V| \le 2N$ and $|E| = N$, which takes $O(N^2)$.
* **Overall Time Complexity:** $\mathcal{O}(N^2)$, which takes around $\sim 10^6$ operations and safely fits well within the 0.5-second time limit.


* **Memory Complexity:** - Storing the binary matrix and `edge_processed` structures requires $\mathcal{O}(N^2)$ memory, which easily fulfills the generous 1024 MB limit.

### Complete C++20 implementation

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <vector>
#include <string>
#include <queue>
#include <algorithm>

using namespace std;

int main() {
    ios_base::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(NULL);

    int N;
    if (!(cin >> N)) return 0;

    vector<string> A(N);
    for (int i = 0; i < N; ++i) {
        cin >> A[i];
    }

    vector<vector<bool>> edge_processed(N, vector<bool>(N, false));
    vector<int> color1(N, -1);
    vector<int> color2(N, -1);
    int C_id = 0;

    for (int u = 0; u < N; ++u) {
        for (int v = u + 1; v < N; ++v) {
            if (A[u][v] == '1' && !edge_processed[u][v]) {
                vector<int> C;
                C.push_back(u);
                C.push_back(v);
                for (int x = 0; x < N; ++x) {
                    if (x != u && x != v && A[u][x] == '1' && A[v][x] == '1') {
                        C.push_back(x);
                    }
                }
                C_id++;
                for (int x : C) {
                    if (color1[x] == -1) color1[x] = C_id;
                    else if (color2[x] == -1) color2[x] = C_id;
                }
                for (int i = 0; i < C.size(); ++i) {
                    for (int j = i + 1; j < C.size(); ++j) {
                        edge_processed[C[i]][C[j]] = true;
                        edge_processed[C[j]][C[i]] = true;
                    }
                }
            }
        }
    }

    for (int i = 0; i < N; ++i) {
        if (color1[i] == -1) color1[i] = ++C_id;
        if (color2[i] == -1) color2[i] = ++C_id;
    }

    vector<vector<int>> adj(C_id + 1);
    for (int i = 0; i < N; ++i) {
        adj[color1[i]].push_back(color2[i]);
        adj[color2[i]].push_back(color1[i]);
    }

    vector<int> side(C_id + 1, -1);
    for (int i = 1; i <= C_id; ++i) {
        if (side[i] == -1) {
            side[i] = 0;
            queue<int> q;
            q.push(i);
            while (!q.empty()) {
                int u = q.front();
                q.pop();
                for (int v : adj[u]) {
                    if (side[v] == -1) {
                        side[v] = 1 - side[u];
                        q.push(v);
                    }
                }
            }
        }
    }

    vector<vector<int>> match_adj(C_id + 1);
    for (int i = 0; i < N; ++i) {
        int u = color1[i];
        int v = color2[i];
        if (side[u] == 1) swap(u, v);
        match_adj[u].push_back(v);
    }

    vector<int> match(C_id + 1, -1);
    vector<bool> vis(C_id + 1, false);

    auto dfs = [&](auto& self, int u) -> bool {
        for (int v : match_adj[u]) {
            if (vis[v]) continue;
            vis[v] = true;
            if (match[v] == -1 || self(self, match[v])) {
                match[v] = u;
                return true;
            }
        }
        return false;
    };

    int max_match = 0;
    for (int i = 1; i <= C_id; ++i) {
        if (side[i] == 0) {
            fill(vis.begin(), vis.end(), false);
            if (dfs(dfs, i)) {
                max_match++;
            }
        }
    }

    cout << max_match << "\n";
    return 0;
}

