### Main idea

The problem asks for the $K$-th permutation of $1 \dots N$ sorted first by the number of inversions, and then lexicographically.
The number of permutations of length $n$ with $k$ inversions can be computed using dynamic programming. Because $K \le 4 \cdot 10^{18}$, the maximum number of inversions $M$ we ever need to consider is surprisingly small. Even for large $N$, the cumulative number of permutations reaches $4 \cdot 10^{18}$ well before 200 inversions (in fact, $M \le 190$ is sufficient for any $N$).
By capping our DP values at an infinity threshold ($> 4 \cdot 10^{18}$), we can precompute a DP table of size $N \times 205$. Afterward, we determine the exact number of inversions $I$ for the target permutation. Finally, we greedily determine the elements from left to right. At each step, picking the $v$-th smallest available number (0-indexed) contributes exactly $v$ inversions, allowing us to subtract branches from $K$ and locate the correct element in $O(\log N)$ using a Binary Indexed Tree.

### Technique used

Dynamic Programming, Greedy Lexicographical Construction, and a Binary Indexed Tree (Fenwick Tree) for efficient order statistics.

### Correctness argument

Let $dp[n][k]$ be the number of permutations of length $n$ with $k$ inversions.
For $n \le k$, we use the exact $O(k)$ transition: $dp[n][k] = \sum_{v=0}^{\min(k, n-1)} dp[n-1][k-v]$.
For $n > k$, the exact $O(1)$ transition is perfectly bounded: $dp[n][k] = dp[n][k-1] + dp[n-1][k]$.
Since we cap DP addition strictly at $4 \cdot 10^{18} + 5$, and $n > k$ requires no subtractions, exact values for reachable states are never lost. When reconstructing the permutation, we subtract the exact number of valid permutations for bypassed lexicographical choices. Because the exact sum of sub-branches matches the parent branch, we are guaranteed to find a valid $v$-th smallest unpicked number safely.

### Complexity analysis

* **Time Complexity:** $O(N \cdot M + N \log N)$, where $M = 205$ is the maximum inversions considered. The DP takes $O(N \cdot M)$ time, and generating the permutation takes $N$ queries on the Binary Indexed Tree, costing $O(N \log N)$. This effortlessly passes within the 0.5s limit.
* **Space/Memory Complexity:** $O(N \cdot M)$. The global DP table takes $200005 \times 206 \times 8 \text{ bytes} \approx 330 \text{ MB}$, well within the generous $1024 \text{ MB}$ limit.

### Complete C++20 implementation

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <vector>
#include <algorithm>

using namespace std;

const int MAXN = 200005;
const int MAXM = 206;
const long long INF = 4000000000000000005LL;

long long dp[MAXN][MAXM];

struct BIT {
    int n;
    vector<int> tree;
    BIT(int n) : n(n), tree(n + 1, 0) {
        for (int i = 1; i <= n; i++) {
            add(i, 1);
        }
    }
    void add(int i, int delta) {
        for (; i <= n; i += i & -i) {
            tree[i] += delta;
        }
    }
    int find_kth(int k) {
        int pos = 0;
        int sum = 0;
        for (int i = 18; i >= 0; i--) {
            if (pos + (1 << i) <= n && sum + tree[pos + (1 << i)] < k) {
                sum += tree[pos + (1 << i)];
                pos += (1 << i);
            }
        }
        return pos + 1;
    }
};

int main() {
    ios_base::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(NULL);

    int N;
    long long K;
    if (!(cin >> N >> K)) return 0;

    for (int i = 0; i <= N; ++i) {
        dp[i][0] = 1;
    }
    for (int j = 1; j < MAXM; ++j) {
        dp[0][j] = 0;
    }

    for (int i = 1; i <= N; ++i) {
        for (int j = 1; j < MAXM; ++j) {
            if (i <= j) {
                long long ways = 0;
                for (int v = 0; v < i && v <= j; ++v) {
                    ways += dp[i - 1][j - v];
                    if (ways > INF) {
                        ways = INF;
                        break;
                    }
                }
                dp[i][j] = ways;
            } else {
                long long ways = dp[i][j - 1] + dp[i - 1][j];
                if (ways > INF) ways = INF;
                dp[i][j] = ways;
            }
        }
    }

    int I = 0;
    long long current_sum = 0;
    while (I < MAXM) {
        long long ways = dp[N][I];
        if (K - current_sum <= ways) {
            break;
        }
        current_sum += ways;
        I++;
    }
    K -= current_sum;

    BIT bit(N);
    for (int i = 1; i <= N; ++i) {
        int rem = N - i + 1;
        int chosen_v = -1;

        int limit = min(I, rem - 1);
        for (int v = 0; v <= limit; ++v) {
            long long ways = dp[rem - 1][I - v];
            if (K <= ways) {
                chosen_v = v;
                break;
            }
            K -= ways;
        }

        int val = bit.find_kth(chosen_v + 1);
        cout << val << (i == N ? "" : " ");

        bit.add(val, -1);
        I -= chosen_v;
    }
    cout << "\n";

    return 0;
}

