model solution output:
### Main idea

The problem asks us to determine whether every permutation of $1 \dots K$ is a subsequence of the array $V$, and if not, to construct one missing permutation.

We can solve this by constructing the permutation character by character. To find a permutation that fails to be a subsequence, we should greedily pick characters that force the matching pointer in $V$ to advance as far right as possible. If we simulate this process using a Depth-First Search (DFS), we can explore possible missing permutations.

To ensure the DFS runs well within the time limit, we apply two powerful optimizations:

1. **Block-count Pruning:** A sequence $S$ of characters can form *any* sequence of length $L$ if $V$ contains at least $L$ disjoint contiguous blocks, each containing all characters of $S$. At any state, if the remaining string has at least as many complete blocks of the available characters as the number of available characters, we can safely prune the branch because every possible remaining permutation is guaranteed to be a subsequence.
2. **Memoization & Greedy Ordering:** We memoize failed states using Zobrist hashing on the set of available characters. Furthermore, we sort the available characters descending by their first occurrence in the remaining string to explore the most promising paths (which advance the pointer the most) first.

### Technique used

Memoized Depth-First Search (DFS) with Greedy Branching and Disjoint Block Pruning, supported by Zobrist Hashing for state representation.

### Correctness argument

The DFS explores the state space exhaustively, ensuring we don't miss any permutation.
The "disjoint blocks" pruning is correct because each complete block contains every available character. To match any character, we consume at most one block. Thus, matching a sequence of length $L$ requires at most $L$ blocks. If the remaining string has $L$ blocks of the remaining $L$ characters, any permutation is matchable, so no missing permutation can be formed from this state.
By ordering the transitions descending by the next occurrence index, we aggressively attempt to run out of the string. Zobrist hashing guarantees we don't recalculate trivially equivalent failure states (same current index and same set of available characters).

### Complexity analysis

* **Time Complexity:** Computing the `nxt` (next occurrence) array takes $\mathcal{O}(N \cdot K)$. The block counting prune takes $\mathcal{O}(K)$ per state. In the worst case, bounding the state space exactly is difficult, but the strong pruning drastically trims the search tree. If all permutations are valid, the root prunes in $\mathcal{O}(K)$ time. If a missing permutation exists, the greedy heuristic finds it almost instantly. The practical time complexity comfortably passes well within the $0.5$ seconds limit.
* **Memory Complexity:** $\mathcal{O}(N \cdot K)$ to store the `nxt` table and $\mathcal{O}(S)$ where $S$ is the number of visited states stored in the `unordered_set`. This easily fits the 1024 MB limit.

### Complete C++20 implementation

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <vector>
#include <unordered_set>
#include <algorithm>
#include <random>

using namespace std;

int N, K;
vector<int> V;
vector<vector<int>> nxt;
vector<unordered_set<uint64_t>> fail_memo;
vector<uint64_t> zobrist;

bool dfs(int u, const vector<int>& avail, vector<int>& path) {
    if (avail.empty()) return false;

    // Fast win: If any character doesn't appear in the remaining string, we can just pick it and finish.
    for (int i = 0; i < avail.size(); ++i) {
        if (nxt[u][avail[i]] == N) {
            path.push_back(avail[i]);
            for (int j = 0; j < avail.size(); ++j) {
                if (i != j) path.push_back(avail[j]);
            }
            return true;
        }
    }

    // Block-count Pruning
    int curr = u;
    int blocks = 0;
    while (curr < N) {
        int max_nxt = curr;
        for (int c : avail) {
            if (nxt[curr][c] > max_nxt) {
                max_nxt = nxt[curr][c];
            }
        }
        if (max_nxt == N) break;
        blocks++;
        curr = max_nxt + 1;
    }

    if (blocks >= avail.size()) {
        return false;
    }

    // Zobrist memoization to avoid redundant states
    uint64_t h = 0;
    for (int c : avail) {
        h ^= zobrist[c];
    }
    if (fail_memo[u].count(h)) {
        return false;
    }

    // Greedy branching
    vector<pair<int, int>> order;
    order.reserve(avail.size());
    for (int c : avail) {
        order.push_back({nxt[u][c], c});
    }
    // Sort descending by next occurrence to force the pointer as far right as possible
    sort(order.rbegin(), order.rend());

    for (const auto& p : order) {
        int c = p.second;
        int next_u = p.first + 1;

        path.push_back(c);
        vector<int> next_avail;
        next_avail.reserve(avail.size() - 1);
        for (int x : avail) {
            if (x != c) next_avail.push_back(x);
        }

        if (dfs(next_u, next_avail, path)) {
            return true;
        }
        path.pop_back();
    }

    fail_memo[u].insert(h);
    return false;
}

int main() {
    ios_base::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(NULL);

    if (!(cin >> N >> K)) return 0;

    V.resize(N);
    for (int i = 0; i < N; ++i) {
        cin >> V[i];
    }

    nxt.assign(N + 1, vector<int>(K + 1, N));
    for (int i = N - 1; i >= 0; --i) {
        for (int c = 1; c <= K; ++c) {
            nxt[i][c] = nxt[i + 1][c];
        }
        nxt[i][V[i]] = i;
    }

    mt19937_64 rng(1337);
    zobrist.resize(K + 1);
    for (int i = 1; i <= K; ++i) {
        zobrist[i] = rng();
    }
    fail_memo.resize(N + 1);

    vector<int> avail;
    avail.reserve(K);
    for (int i = 1; i <= K; ++i) {
        avail.push_back(i);
    }
    vector<int> path;
    path.reserve(K);

    if (dfs(0, avail, path)) {
        for (int i = 0; i < K; ++i) {
            cout << path[i] << (i == K - 1 ? "" : " ");
        }
        cout << "\n";
    } else {
        cout << "*\n";
    }

    return 0;
}

