### Main idea

The problem requires finding an optimal sequence of visiting cities on a tree to maximize the profit formula $\sum_{i=1}^{N} i \times p_i$ , starting at city $R$. Because the road network has N-1 transfers connecting all N cities, it forms a spanning tree. You can visit any unvisited city as long as it is adjacent to a previously visited one.

To maximize the profit sum, we must assign smaller multipliers $i$ to smaller popularity indices $p_i$, meaning we want to visit cities with smaller popularity values as early as possible. If a city $u$ has a smaller average popularity than its directed parent $p$, it is strictly optimal to visit $u$ immediately after $p$. We can continuously merge the component with the minimum average popularity into its parent component, effectively concatenating their visit sequences.

### Technique used

Greedy Algorithm with Disjoint Set Union (DSU) and a Priority Queue.

### Correctness argument

By the problem rules, the tour starts at city R and can expand dynamically through the tree. Our goal is to greedily pick the smallest available node. However, a small node might be blocked by a parent with a larger popularity index.

* By treating each node as a sequence block, we evaluate blocks based on their average value $\frac{\text{Sum}}{\text{Count}}$.
* When a block $u$ has the smallest average value in the available graph, we know that in the optimal sequence, $u$ must be executed immediately after its tree parent block $p$.
* We can merge $u$ into $p$, creating a combined block with updated sums and element counts, and concatenate $u$'s visiting order to the end of $p$'s.
* Using a DSU helps us efficiently track which block a node currently belongs to, while a min-heap (Priority Queue) prioritizes the block with the smallest average.

### Complexity analysis

* **Time Complexity:** $\mathcal{O}(N \log N)$. Running a BFS to build the directed tree from $R$ takes linear time. Constructing the initial elements takes $\mathcal{O}(N)$. There are at most $N-1$ successful merges. Each merge takes near $\mathcal{O}(1)$ time using DSU path compression and adds at most one new element to the Priority Queue. Priority Queue operations take $\mathcal{O}(\log N)$, leading to a dominant $\mathcal{O}(N \log N)$ complexity.


* **Memory Complexity:** $\mathcal{O}(N)$. The graph structure, DSU state arrays, and Priority Queue elements scale linearly with $N$. This comfortably fits well within the generous 1024 MB limit.



### Complete C++20 implementation

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <vector>
#include <queue>

using namespace std;

struct Block {
    long long s, n;
    int id;
    bool operator<(const Block& other) const {
        if (s * other.n != other.s * n) {
            return s * other.n > other.s * n;
        }
        return id > other.id;
    }
};

const int MAXN = 300005;
int parent_dsu[MAXN];
long long S[MAXN];
long long N_cnt[MAXN];
int head_node[MAXN];
int tail_node[MAXN];
int nxt[MAXN];
int par[MAXN];
vector<int> adj[MAXN];

int find_set(int v) {
    if (v == parent_dsu[v])
        return v;
    return parent_dsu[v] = find_set(parent_dsu[v]);
}

int main() {
    ios_base::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(NULL);

    int N, R;
    if (!(cin >> N >> R)) return 0;

    for (int i = 0; i < N - 1; ++i) {
        int u, v;
        cin >> u >> v;
        adj[u].push_back(v);
        adj[v].push_back(u);
    }

    vector<int> q;
    q.push_back(R);
    int q_head = 0;
    while (q_head < (int)q.size()) {
        int u = q[q_head++];
        for (int v : adj[u]) {
            if (v != par[u]) {
                par[v] = u;
                q.push_back(v);
            }
        }
    }

    priority_queue<Block> pq;
    for (int i = 1; i <= N; ++i) {
        parent_dsu[i] = i;
        S[i] = i;
        N_cnt[i] = 1;
        head_node[i] = i;
        tail_node[i] = i;
        nxt[i] = 0;
        if (i != R) {
            pq.push({S[i], N_cnt[i], i});
        }
    }

    while (!pq.empty()) {
        Block b = pq.top();
        pq.pop();

        int u = b.id;
        if (u != find_set(u) || S[u] != b.s || N_cnt[u] != b.n) {
            continue;
        }

        int p = find_set(par[u]);
        parent_dsu[u] = p;
        S[p] += S[u];
        N_cnt[p] += N_cnt[u];
        nxt[tail_node[p]] = head_node[u];
        tail_node[p] = tail_node[u];

        if (p != R) {
            pq.push({S[p], N_cnt[p], p});
        }
    }

    long long ans = 0;
    long long pos = 1;
    int curr = R;

    while (curr != 0) {
        ans += pos * curr;
        pos++;
        curr = nxt[curr];
    }

    cout << ans << "\n";

    return 0;
}

