### Main idea

To achieve exactly $K$ different types of cake pieces using the minimum number of machine runs, we must perform $T = \lceil \log_2 K \rceil$ runs.

We can systematically generate the required types by designing a single large "comb-shaped" connected component (let's call it $C$) on the $100 \times 100$ grid. The comb $C$ consists of a vertical backbone on the first column and horizontal teeth on every odd-numbered row. Because $C$ is a single connected block, we can safely include it in *every* machine run, meaning every cell in $C$ will receive the "all-1" topping combination (representing $T$ toppings).

The spaces between the teeth of the comb act as isolated "slots" (located on even-numbered rows, from the second column onward). There are $50 \times 99 = 4950$ such slots. Because every slot is directly adjacent to a tooth of the comb, adding any subset of slots to $C$ will keep the entire collection connected.

To generate exactly $K$ types, we select $K-2$ of these slots and assign each a unique binary value from $1$ to $K-2$. For the $j$-th machine run, we apply a topping to all cells in $C$, as well as to any assigned slot whose binary value has the $j$-th bit set. This process guarantees exactly $K$ combinations on the grid: the empty combination (on the unused slots), the all-1 combination (on $C$), and the uniquely assigned binary combinations on the $K-2$ slots.

### Technique used

Constructive algorithms, bitmasking, and graph embedding on a grid.

### Correctness argument

1. **Minimum runs requirement:** Since $T$ runs can produce at most $2^T$ distinct types of pieces, $T = \lceil \log_2 K \rceil$ is theoretically the absolute minimum number of times the machine must be used to get $K$ types.
2. **Connectivity invariant:** In each run $j$, the subset of selected cells is $S_j = C \cup \{ \text{slots with bit } j \text{ set} \}$. $C$ is inherently connected by construction. Because every slot is directly bounded by the cells of $C$ (the teeth above and below it), any slot added to $C$ is directly connected to $C$. Therefore, $S_j$ is always a strictly connected component, satisfying the machine's requirement.
3. **Exact type generation:** By construction, the combinations produced are the integer $0$ (for all unassigned slots), the integer $2^T-1$ (for $C$), and the integers $1$ through $K-2$ (for the assigned slots). Since $K \le 2^T$, the maximum assigned value $K-2$ is strictly less than $2^T-1$. Thus, no assigned slot accidentally duplicates the all-1 type. This results in exactly $1 + 1 + (K - 2) = K$ different combinations.

### Complexity analysis

* **Time Complexity:** $\mathcal{O}(R \cdot C \cdot T)$ where $R = 100$ and $C = 100$ are the dimensions of the grid, and $T \le 12$. Constructing the comb and iterating over up to $K$ slots takes at most $\sim 10^4$ operations per machine run. Across $\le 12$ runs, it yields $\approx 1.2 \times 10^5$ operations, which easily runs within the 0.3 seconds limit.
* **Memory Complexity:** $\mathcal{O}(R \cdot C)$ to store the coordinate pairs of $C$ and the slots. This requires a few vectors of size at most $10000$, well within the 1024 MB limit.

### Complete C++20 implementation

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <vector>

using namespace std;

int main() {
    ios_base::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(NULL);

    int K;
    if (!(cin >> K)) return 0;

    if (K == 1) {
        cout << 0 << "\n";
        return 0;
    }

    int T = 0;
    while ((1 << T) < K) {
        T++;
    }

    cout << T << "\n";

    vector<pair<int, int>> C;
    for (int r = 1; r <= 100; ++r) {
        C.push_back({r, 1});
    }
    for (int r = 1; r <= 100; r += 2) {
        for (int c = 2; c <= 100; ++c) {
            C.push_back({r, c});
        }
    }

    vector<pair<int, int>> slots;
    for (int r = 2; r <= 100; r += 2) {
        for (int c = 2; c <= 100; ++c) {
            slots.push_back({r, c});
        }
    }

    for (int j = 0; j < T; ++j) {
        vector<pair<int, int>> Sj = C;
        for (int x = 1; x <= K - 2; ++x) {
            if ((x >> j) & 1) {
                Sj.push_back(slots[x - 1]);
            }
        }
        cout << Sj.size();
        for (auto& p : Sj) {
            cout << " " << p.first << " " << p.second;
        }
        cout << "\n";
    }

    return 0;
}

