### Main idea

The problem asks whether $T_2$ is isomorphic to any subtree of $T_1$. This can be modeled as finding an injective mapping from the vertices of $T_2$ to $T_1$ that preserves adjacency. By arbitrarily rooting $T_2$ at vertex 1, we can attempt to map this root to every possible vertex $R$ in $T_1$. For a fixed mapping of $T_2$'s root to $R \in T_1$, we recursively check if the children of each node in $T_2$ can be injectively mapped to the children of the corresponding node in $T_1$. Since a node in $T_1$ might have multiple valid assignments for the children of $T_2$, we formulate this assignment step as finding a maximum bipartite matching.

### Technique used

* **Tree Dynamic Programming**: To memoize the states of matching subtrees.
* **Maximum Bipartite Matching (Hopcroft-Karp / DFS)**: To optimally assign the children of a node in $T_2$ to distinct children of a mapped node in $T_1$.

### Correctness argument

Any isomorphic embedding of $T_2$ into $T_1$ will map vertex 1 of $T_2$ to some vertex $R \in T_1$. When we treat $T_2$ as rooted at 1 and $T_1$ as rooted at $R$, the embedding must map the subtrees of $T_2$ (rooted at the children of 1) to disjoint subtrees of $T_1$ (rooted at the children of $R$).

By defining our state as `dp(u, pu, v)`, meaning "can the subtree of $T_2$ rooted at $v$ be embedded in the subtree of $T_1$ rooted at $u$ (where $u$'s parent is $pu$)?", we accurately capture the subtree restriction. The bipartite matching correctly verifies if there is any valid injective assignment of $v$'s children to $u$'s available branches. Memoization ensures each overlapping subproblem (a mapping between a directed edge in $T_1$ and a directed edge in $T_2$) is evaluated only once, guaranteeing both correctness and efficiency.

### Complexity analysis

* **Time Complexity:** The state space for `dp(u, pu, v)` is bounded by the number of directed edges in $T_1$ multiplied by the number of vertices in $T_2$, which is $O(N_1 \cdot N_2)$. At each state, we build and solve a bipartite matching problem where the left side $L$ is the number of children of $v$ and the right side $R$ is the number of children of $u$. The DFS matching takes $O(L \cdot R)$. Summing this over all states, the maximum number of operations is bounded by $\mathcal{O}(N_1^2 \cdot N_2 \cdot d_{max})$, where $d_{max}$ is the maximum degree. In the worst case, this evaluates to roughly $\mathcal{O}(N^4) \approx 10^8$ operations, executing comfortably within the 0.5 s time limit.
* **Memory/Space Complexity:** $\mathcal{O}(N_1^2 \cdot N_2)$ for the 3D memoization array. For $N_1, N_2 \le 100$, this requires $105 \times 105 \times 105 \times 4 \text{ bytes} \approx 4.6 \text{ MB}$, well within the 1024 MB threshold.

### Complete C++20 implementation

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <vector>
#include <algorithm>

using namespace std;

int N1, N2;
vector<int> adj1[105];
vector<int> adj2[105];
vector<int> children2[105];

void build_tree2(int u, int p) {
    for (int nxt : adj2[u]) {
        if (nxt != p) {
            children2[u].push_back(nxt);
            build_tree2(nxt, u);
        }
    }
}

int memo[105][105][105];

int solve(int u, int pu, int v) {
    if (memo[u][pu][v] != -1) {
        return memo[u][pu][v];
    }

    vector<int> Cu;
    for (int nxt : adj1[u]) {
        if (nxt != pu) {
            Cu.push_back(nxt);
        }
    }

    const vector<int>& Cv = children2[v];

    if (Cv.size() > Cu.size()) {
        return memo[u][pu][v] = 0;
    }

    int L = Cv.size();
    int R = Cu.size();

    if (L == 0) {
        return memo[u][pu][v] = 1;
    }

    vector<vector<int>> adj_bip(L);
    for (int i = 0; i < L; ++i) {
        for (int j = 0; j < R; ++j) {
            if (solve(Cu[j], u, Cv[i])) {
                adj_bip[i].push_back(j);
            }
        }
    }

    vector<int> match(R, -1);
    vector<int> vis(R, 0);

    auto dfs = [&](auto& self, int i) -> bool {
        for (int j : adj_bip[i]) {
            if (vis[j]) continue;
            vis[j] = 1;
            if (match[j] == -1 || self(self, match[j])) {
                match[j] = i;
                return true;
            }
        }
        return false;
    };

    int matches = 0;
    for (int i = 0; i < L; ++i) {
        fill(vis.begin(), vis.end(), 0);
        if (dfs(dfs, i)) {
            matches++;
        }
    }

    return memo[u][pu][v] = (matches == L ? 1 : 0);
}

int main() {
    ios_base::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(NULL);

    if (!(cin >> N1)) return 0;

    for (int i = 0; i < N1 - 1; ++i) {
        int u, v;
        cin >> u >> v;
        adj1[u].push_back(v);
        adj1[v].push_back(u);
    }

    cin >> N2;
    for (int i = 0; i < N2 - 1; ++i) {
        int u, v;
        cin >> u >> v;
        adj2[u].push_back(v);
        adj2[v].push_back(u);
    }

    if (N2 > N1) {
        cout << "N\n";
        return 0;
    }

    build_tree2(1, 0);

    for (int i = 0; i <= N1; ++i) {
        for (int j = 0; j <= N1; ++j) {
            for (int k = 0; k <= N2; ++k) {
                memo[i][j][k] = -1;
            }
        }
    }

    bool possible = false;
    for (int i = 1; i <= N1; ++i) {
        if (solve(i, 0, 1)) {
            possible = true;
            break;
        }
    }

    if (possible) {
        cout << "Y\n";
    } else {
        cout << "N\n";
    }

    return 0;
}

