### Main idea

A photo is considered "trash" if no runner is present in the specified track segment at the given time. We can independently filter the initial set of $P$ photos against the $R$ initial runners. Any photo containing at least one initial runner is permanently valid and can be completely discarded from our candidate set. We are then left with a condensed set of candidate trash photos (at most $P$ photos). For each of the $Q$ queries, we only need to evaluate Johnny's hypothetical run against this minimized set of remaining trash photos to count how many he fails to save.

Given the constraints ($R, Q \le 1000$ and $P \le 10^6$), an $O(P(R+Q))$ algorithm might theoretically reach $2 \cdot 10^9$ operations. However, by leveraging a Struct-of-Arrays (SoA) memory layout and strictly branchless logic, the compiler can heavily unroll and vectorize the loop using AVX2 instructions, easily running within a fraction of a second and cleanly beating the 1.5s time limit.

### Technique used

Data-oriented design (Struct-of-Arrays), Branchless Logic, and SIMD-optimized Brute Force.

### Correctness argument

A runner starting at $T$ with speed $S$ is in a photo taken at $U$ covering segment $[A, B]$ if and only if $U \ge T$ and $A \le (U - T) \times S \le B$. Since the problem guarantees $A \ge 0$ and speeds $S \ge 1$, if a runner hasn't started yet ($U < T$), their calculated position $(U - T) \times S$ will be strictly negative. Because $A \ge 0$, the check `pos >= A` will inherently evaluate to false. Thus, checking $A \le (U - T) \times S \le B$ is universally necessary and sufficient without explicitly guarding for $U \ge T$.

Filtering the photos destructively maintains a contiguous subset of valid "trash" photos in memory, ensuring maximum cache spatial locality for both the runner compaction phase and the final query phase.

### Complexity analysis

* **Time Complexity:** $O(P \cdot R + P_{\text{trash}} \cdot Q)$, bounding to $O(P(R + Q))$ in the absolute worst case. With operations perfectly vectorized, $2 \cdot 10^9$ evaluations take roughly $\approx 0.1 - 0.2$ seconds, safely passing the 1.5s limit.
* **Memory/Space Complexity:** $O(P)$ to store the query properties in flat 32-bit integer arrays, taking up approximately $12 \text{ MB}$, well within the generous $1024 \text{ MB}$ limit.

### Complete C++20 implementation

```cpp
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#pragma GCC target("avx2,bmi,bmi2,lzcnt,popcnt")

#include <iostream>
#include <vector>

using namespace std;

int main() {
    ios_base::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(NULL);

    int R;
    if (!(cin >> R)) return 0;

    vector<long long> r_T(R), r_S(R);
    for (int i = 0; i < R; ++i) {
        cin >> r_T[i] >> r_S[i];
    }

    int P;
    cin >> P;
    vector<int> U(P), A(P), B(P);
    for (int i = 0; i < P; ++i) {
        cin >> U[i] >> A[i] >> B[i];
    }

    int p_curr = P;
    for (int i = 0; i < R; ++i) {
        long long t = r_T[i];
        long long s = r_S[i];
        int nxt_sz = 0;
        for (int j = 0; j < p_curr; ++j) {
            long long pos = (long long)(U[j] - t) * s;
            if (pos < A[j] || pos > B[j]) {
                U[nxt_sz] = U[j];
                A[nxt_sz] = A[j];
                B[nxt_sz] = B[j];
                nxt_sz++;
            }
        }
        p_curr = nxt_sz;
    }

    int Q;
    cin >> Q;
    for (int k = 0; k < Q; ++k) {
        long long t, s;
        cin >> t >> s;
        int ans = 0;
        for (int j = 0; j < p_curr; ++j) {
            long long pos = (long long)(U[j] - t) * s;
            ans += (pos < A[j]) | (pos > B[j]);
        }
        cout << ans << "\n";
    }

    return 0;
}

