### Main idea

Any edge in a tree splits it into two disjoint components, say $A$ and $B$. A path connecting two vertices $u$ and $v$ crosses this edge if and only if one vertex is in component $A$ and the other is in component $B$.

If we fix a color $c$, the number of valid pairs $(u, v)$ where both have color $c$ is exactly the number of nodes of color $c$ in component $A$ multiplied by the number of nodes of color $c$ in component $B$. If we define $S_c$ as the total number of nodes of color $c$ in the entire tree, and $cnt_c$ as the count in component $A$, then the count in component $B$ is exactly $S_c - cnt_c$. The total number of tedious paths crossing the edge is $\sum_{c=1}^N cnt_c \times (S_c - cnt_c)$. Rooting the tree arbitrarily allows us to dynamically compute this sum for the subtree components efficiently.

### Technique used

DSU on Trees (Sack Algorithm) / Small-to-Large merging.

### Correctness argument

By rooting the tree at vertex 1, every edge can be identified by the child node it points to. For any subtree rooted at $v$, its vertices form component $A$ of the split produced by the edge connecting $v$ to its parent.

A naive computation of the color frequencies for every subtree takes $O(N^2)$ time. The DSU on Trees algorithm optimizes this by retaining the frequencies of the largest child subtree (heavy child) and recomputing only the smaller ones (light children).

When a node of color $c$ is added to our current subtree frequency count (i.e., $cnt_c$ increments by 1), the isolated contribution $cnt_c \times (S_c - cnt_c)$ shifts algebraically:
$\Delta = (cnt_c + 1)(S_c - (cnt_c + 1)) - cnt_c(S_c - cnt_c) = S_c - 2 \cdot cnt_c - 1$
Applying this $O(1)$ arithmetic change synchronously with the DSU on Trees updates guarantees we always have the accurate total answer evaluated by the time we fully traverse a subtree and record the result for the edge above it.

### Complexity analysis

* **Time Complexity:** $\mathcal{O}(N \log N)$. In DSU on Trees, the state of the heavy child is kept, and light children's sizes at least double up the ancestral chain. Thus, each of the $N$ nodes is added and removed from the global frequency array at most $\mathcal{O}(\log N)$ times. Processing an individual node update operates in $\mathcal{O}(1)$ time.
* **Memory Complexity:** $\mathcal{O}(N)$. Adjacency lists, recursive depths, and auxiliary tree arrays (`sz`, `big`, `cnt`, `total_cnt`, `ans`) linearly scale with $N$.

### Complete C++20 implementation

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <vector>

using namespace std;

const int MAXN = 100005;
int n;
int color[MAXN];
int total_cnt[MAXN];
int cnt[MAXN];
long long ans[MAXN];
long long current_ans = 0;

struct Edge {
    int to;
    int id;
};
vector<Edge> adj[MAXN];

int sz[MAXN], big[MAXN];

void dfs_sz(int v, int p) {
    sz[v] = 1;
    big[v] = -1;
    int max_sub = 0;
    for (auto edge : adj[v]) {
        int u = edge.to;
        if (u != p) {
            dfs_sz(u, v);
            sz[v] += sz[u];
            if (sz[u] > max_sub) {
                max_sub = sz[u];
                big[v] = u;
            }
        }
    }
}

inline void update_node(int v, int delta) {
    int c = color[v];
    if (delta == 1) {
        int x = cnt[c];
        current_ans += (long long)total_cnt[c] - 2LL * x - 1LL;
        cnt[c]++;
    } else {
        int x = cnt[c] - 1;
        current_ans -= (long long)total_cnt[c] - 2LL * x - 1LL;
        cnt[c]--;
    }
}

void update_subtree(int v, int p, int skip, int delta) {
    update_node(v, delta);
    for (auto edge : adj[v]) {
        int u = edge.to;
        if (u != p && u != skip) {
            update_subtree(u, v, skip, delta);
        }
    }
}

void dfs_dsu(int v, int p, int edge_id, bool keep) {
    for (auto edge : adj[v]) {
        int u = edge.to;
        if (u != p && u != big[v]) {
            dfs_dsu(u, v, edge.id, false);
        }
    }

    if (big[v] != -1) {
        int heavy_id = -1;
        for (auto edge : adj[v]) {
            if (edge.to == big[v]) {
                heavy_id = edge.id;
                break;
            }
        }
        dfs_dsu(big[v], v, heavy_id, true);
    }

    update_node(v, 1);
    for (auto edge : adj[v]) {
        int u = edge.to;
        if (u != p && u != big[v]) {
            update_subtree(u, v, -1, 1);
        }
    }

    if (edge_id != -1) {
        ans[edge_id] = current_ans;
    }

    if (!keep) {
        update_subtree(v, p, -1, -1);
    }
}

int main() {
    ios_base::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(NULL);

    if (!(cin >> n)) return 0;

    for (int i = 1; i <= n; ++i) {
        cin >> color[i];
        total_cnt[color[i]]++;
    }

    for (int i = 0; i < n - 1; ++i) {
        int u, v;
        cin >> u >> v;
        adj[u].push_back({v, i});
        adj[v].push_back({u, i});
    }

    dfs_sz(1, 0);
    dfs_dsu(1, 0, -1, true);

    for (int i = 0; i < n - 1; ++i) {
        cout << ans[i] << (i == n - 2 ? "" : " ");
    }
    cout << "\n";

    return 0;
}

```

