model solution output:
### Main idea

The problem requires us to find the first round in which each participant's position becomes $\le 0$. A participant $i$ moves by $d_q$ in round $q$ if they share a common prime factor with $c_q$, which is mathematically equivalent to $\gcd(i, c_q) > 1$.

Since a participant's distance monotonically increases over the rounds, we can use Parallel Binary Search. For each participant, we maintain a search space $[L, R]$ (initially $[1, Q]$) of the rounds. In each iteration, we group participants by the midpoint of their search range (`mid = (L + R) / 2`).

To quickly check if a participant has moved enough distance up to round $mid$, we can employ the Inclusion-Exclusion principle over their prime factors. As we process rounds $1$ to $Q$, we update a global frequency-like array $S$ with the distance $d_q$ for every square-free divisor of $c_q$. When we reach round $q = mid$, we can evaluate the participant's total moved distance by adding sums of distances for odd numbers of shared prime factors and subtracting for even numbers of shared prime factors.

### Technique used

* Parallel Binary Search
* Number Theory (Prime Factorization, Inclusion-Exclusion)

### Correctness argument

Using Parallel Binary Search is valid because the cumulative distance a participant travels is non-decreasing. Finding the earliest round is structurally a lower-bound search.
For evaluating the distance properly, let $P(i)$ be the set of distinct prime factors of $i$. The condition $\gcd(i, c_q) > 1$ is satisfied if and only if $c_q$ is a multiple of at least one prime $p \in P(i)$. By maintaining the sum of distances for every square-free divisor of the round's multiplier $c_q$, we can precisely apply Inclusion-Exclusion to calculate the total valid distance contributed to participant $i$ without overcounting or undercounting.

### Complexity analysis

* **Time Complexity:** - Precomputation: Factoring all numbers up to $\max(N, C) \le 10^5$ and generating their square-free divisors takes bounded time. Since $10^5$ has at most $6$ distinct prime factors, subsets are small. Overall precomputation is bounded by $O(V \cdot 2^{\omega(V)})$, where $V = 10^5$ and $\omega(V) \le 6$.
* Parallel Binary Search: $\lceil \log_2(Q) \rceil \approx 17$ iterations. In each iteration, we iterate through rounds updating array $S$ and evaluating active participants. With operations bounded by the number of subsets, the cost is $O((Q + N) \cdot 2^{\omega(V)} \cdot \log Q)$.
* Total Time: $\mathcal{O}(V \cdot 2^{\omega(V)} + (N + Q) \cdot 2^{\omega(V)} \log Q)$, running extremely fast and fitting well within the 2.0s limit.


* **Memory Complexity:** The divisor vectors hold $\sum_{i=1}^{V} 2^{\omega(i)} \approx V \log V$ elements. Thus, space complexity is tightly bounded at $\mathcal{O}(V \log V + N + Q)$, well inside the generous 1024 MB limit.

### Complete C++20 implementation

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <vector>
#include <cstring>
#include <algorithm>

using namespace std;

const int MAX = 100005;

int min_prime[MAX];
vector<int> add_divs[MAX];
vector<int> sub_divs[MAX];

int A[MAX];
int C[MAX];
long long D[MAX];

int L[MAX], R[MAX], ans[MAX];
vector<int> mid_queries[MAX];
long long S[MAX];

int main() {
    ios_base::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(NULL);

    for (int i = 2; i < MAX; ++i) {
        if (min_prime[i] == 0) {
            for (int j = i; j < MAX; j += i) {
                if (min_prime[j] == 0) {
                    min_prime[j] = i;
                }
            }
        }
    }

    for (int i = 1; i < MAX; ++i) {
        int temp = i;
        vector<int> primes;
        while (temp > 1) {
            int p = min_prime[temp];
            primes.push_back(p);
            while (temp % p == 0) temp /= p;
        }

        int k = primes.size();
        for (int mask = 1; mask < (1 << k); ++mask) {
            int prod = 1;
            int bits = 0;
            for (int j = 0; j < k; ++j) {
                if ((mask >> j) & 1) {
                    prod *= primes[j];
                    bits++;
                }
            }
            if (bits % 2 == 1) {
                add_divs[i].push_back(prod);
            } else {
                sub_divs[i].push_back(prod);
            }
        }
    }

    int n, q;
    if (!(cin >> n >> q)) return 0;

    for (int i = 1; i <= n; ++i) {
        cin >> A[i];
        L[i] = 1;
        R[i] = q;
        ans[i] = -1;
    }

    for (int i = 1; i <= q; ++i) {
        cin >> C[i] >> D[i];
    }

    bool changed = true;
    while (changed) {
        changed = false;

        for (int i = 1; i <= q; ++i) {
            mid_queries[i].clear();
        }

        int max_mid = 0;
        for (int i = 1; i <= n; ++i) {
            if (L[i] <= R[i]) {
                int mid = L[i] + (R[i] - L[i]) / 2;
                mid_queries[mid].push_back(i);
                if (mid > max_mid) max_mid = mid;
                changed = true;
            }
        }

        if (!changed) break;

        memset(S, 0, sizeof(S));

        for (int i = 1; i <= max_mid; ++i) {
            int c = C[i];
            long long d = D[i];

            for (int m : add_divs[c]) S[m] += d;
            for (int m : sub_divs[c]) S[m] += d;

            for (int idx : mid_queries[i]) {
                long long total = 0;
                for (int m : add_divs[idx]) total += S[m];
                for (int m : sub_divs[idx]) total -= S[m];

                if (total >= A[idx]) {
                    ans[idx] = i;
                    R[idx] = i - 1;
                } else {
                    L[idx] = i + 1;
                }
            }
        }
    }

    for (int i = 1; i <= n; ++i) {
        cout << ans[i] << "\n";
    }

    return 0;
}

```

