### Main idea

Any simple quadrilateral can be identified by its internal diagonal(s). If we draw a line through a diagonal, the other two vertices of the quadrilateral must lie on strictly opposite sides of this line.

* A **convex** quadrilateral has exactly two such diagonals, meaning this property counts it twice.
* A **concave** quadrilateral has exactly one such diagonal, meaning it is naturally counted once.

By iterating over all $N(N-1)/2$ possible diagonals and splitting the remaining points into Left and Right sets using the cross product, we can count the number of valid pairs of points (one on the left, one on the right) that form an area $\ge S$. Let this total sum be $X$.
To correct the double-counting of convex quadrilaterals, we also simultaneously count how many of these valid pairs form a segment that strictly intersects our chosen diagonal. An intersecting diagonal uniquely identifies a convex quadrilateral. Let this intersecting count be $Y$.
The exact number of valid simple quadrilaterals is therefore $X - Y / 2$.

### Technique used

Computational Geometry (Cross Products, Segment Intersection via Projections), Sorting, and Two Pointers.

### Correctness argument

For any diagonal $AB$, we partition the remaining points into $L$ (left side) and $R$ (right side). Any choice of $C \in L$ and $D \in R$ guarantees that the polygon $A \to C \to B \to D \to A$ is non-self-intersecting along the edges connected to $A$ and $B$.
The total area of the quadrilateral is exactly $\text{Area}(ABC) + \text{Area}(ABD)$. If we enforce this area sum to be $\ge S$, we find our candidates.
Checking if the diagonals $AB$ and $CD$ intersect algebraically avoids floating-point errors. The intersection point $P$ must lie strictly between $A$ and $B$. By projecting the vectors onto the line $AB$, we can determine if $P$ falls within the segment bounds solely using 128-bit integer operations to prevent overflow and maintain perfect precision.

### Complexity analysis

* **Time Complexity:** Sorting the $L$ and $R$ sets for each diagonal takes $O(N \log N)$. The two-pointer sweep combined with the inner loop processes at most $3\binom{N}{4}$ pairs over the entire execution. Thus, the time complexity is tightly bounded by $O(N^4)$. Given $N \le 400$, the maximum number of basic operations is roughly $3 \times 10^9$. With an incredibly generous $7.0$ seconds time limit and a branch-free projection check using `__int128_t`, this solution will execute comfortably within the constraints.
* **Space/Memory Complexity:** $O(N)$ auxiliary memory to store the filtered left and right point sets per diagonal.

### Complete C++20 implementation

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <vector>
#include <algorithm>

using namespace std;

struct Point {
    long long x, y;
};

struct Info {
    long long A, D;
    __int128_t W;
    bool operator<(const Info& other) const {
        return A < other.A;
    }
};

int main() {
    ios_base::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(NULL);

    long long S;
    int N;
    if (!(cin >> S >> N)) return 0;
    
    long long S2 = 2 * S;

    vector<Point> P(N);
    for (int i = 0; i < N; ++i) {
        cin >> P[i].x >> P[i].y;
    }

    long long total_pairs = 0;
    long long conv_count = 0;

    vector<Info> L, R;
    L.reserve(N);
    R.reserve(N);

    for (int i = 0; i < N; ++i) {
        for (int j = i + 1; j < N; ++j) {
            Point A = P[i], B = P[j];
            long long L2 = (B.x - A.x) * (B.x - A.x) + (B.y - A.y) * (B.y - A.y);

            L.clear();
            R.clear();

            for (int k = 0; k < N; ++k) {
                if (k == i || k == j) continue;
                long long cross = (B.x - A.x) * (P[k].y - A.y) - (B.y - A.y) * (P[k].x - A.x);
                long long dot = (P[k].x - A.x) * (B.x - A.x) + (P[k].y - A.y) * (B.y - A.y);

                if (cross > 0) {
                    L.push_back({cross, dot, 0});
                } else if (cross < 0) {
                    R.push_back({-cross, dot, (__int128_t)L2 * (-cross)});
                }
            }

            sort(L.begin(), L.end());
            sort(R.begin(), R.end());

            int ptr = R.size();
            for (int k = 0; k < L.size(); ++k) {
                while (ptr > 0 && L[k].A + R[ptr - 1].A >= S2) {
                    ptr--;
                }
                total_pairs += (int)R.size() - ptr;

                long long ac = L[k].A, dc = L[k].D;
                __int128_t L2_ac = (__int128_t)L2 * ac;

                for (int m = ptr; m < R.size(); ++m) {
                    __int128_t K = (__int128_t)dc * R[m].A + (__int128_t)R[m].D * ac;
                    if (K > 0 && K < L2_ac + R[m].W) {
                        conv_count++;
                    }
                }
            }
        }
    }

    cout << total_pairs - conv_count / 2 << "\n";
    return 0;
}

