        coef[0] = c0;

        long long dp_n = 0;
        long long comb = 1;
        for (int j = 0; j <= n; ++j) {
            dp_n = (dp_n + coef[j] * comb) % MOD;
            long long num = (d[n] - j) % MOD;
            comb = comb * num % MOD * inv[j + 1] % MOD;
        }
        dp[n] = dp_n;

        for (int k = 1; k <= n; ++k) {
            long long m = n - k + 1;
            long long num = (d[k] + m) % MOD;
            T[k] = T[k] * num % MOD * inv[m + 1] % MOD;
        }
    }

    cout << dp[N] << "\n";
    return 0;
}

model solution output:
### Main idea

The problem asks for the number of subsets of city leaders to contact such that the resulting active railroad configuration forms exactly one valid path between every pair of cities (a spanning tree). Contacting a leader flips the activation status of all railroads connected to their city. This is exactly equivalent to complementing the edges across the cut $(S, V \setminus S)$, where $S$ is the chosen subset of vertices.

Two subsets $S$ and $V \setminus S$ produce the exact same cut, and thus the same graph structure. Therefore, each unique valid tree generated by these flips corresponds to exactly two distinct valid subsets. Any spanning tree with $N \ge 2$ vertices possesses at least two leaves (vertices with exactly one incident edge). By guessing a leaf $u$ and its unique neighbor $v$, we can completely and deterministically deduce the flip state of all other vertices $w$ required to form that specific tree. By setting $u$'s state to $0$ without loss of generality, we find $s_w = A_{uw} \oplus (w == v ? 1 : 0)$. Iterating through all $N(N-1)$ possible $(u, v)$ pairs allows us to reconstruct every possible valid tree in the switching class without missing any.

### Technique used

Graph Theory (Seidel Switching), Constructive Algorithms, and Set Hashing.

### Correctness argument

By fixing vertex $u$ to have a flip state of 0, the state of any other vertex $w$ is uniquely forced if we demand that $u$ connects exclusively to $v$. Any resulting graph constructed from these states is guaranteed to belong to the switching class of the original graph. By checking all ordered pairs $(u, v)$ for $u \neq v$, we simulate every configuration where $u$ acts as a leaf connected to $v$. Since every tree on $N \ge 2$ has leaves, every valid tree in the switching class will be generated at least once. We serialize the upper triangle of the adjacency matrix of each generated tree and store it in a hash set to efficiently filter out duplicates (since trees with multiple leaves will be found multiple times). Finally, we multiply the number of unique trees by 2 and apply the modulo operation to get the number of distinct good sets.

### Complexity analysis

* **Time Complexity:** $\mathcal{O}(N^4)$. There are $N(N-1)$ pairs of $(u, v)$. For each pair, checking the edges takes $\mathcal{O}(N^2)$. We heavily optimize this by aborting immediately if the number of generated edges strictly exceeds $N-1$. If exactly $N-1$ edges are formed, validating connectivity via Breadth-First Search (BFS) takes $\mathcal{O}(N)$. Given $N \le 100$ , the worst-case number of operations is bounded by $10^8$, safely passing the tight $0.25$ seconds time limit due to the aggressive edge-count pruning.


* **Space Complexity:** $\mathcal{O}(N^3)$. Storing a single graph as a string takes $\mathcal{O}(N^2)$ space. The maximum number of valid trees in a switching class is severely constrained (at most $N(N-1)$), meaning the `std::set` requires at most $\mathcal{O}(N^4)$ in theory but vastly less in practice. This perfectly satisfies the 1024 MB memory limit.



### Complete C++20 implementation

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <vector>
#include <set>
#include <string>

using namespace std;

int main() {
    ios_base::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(NULL);

    int N, M;
    if (!(cin >> N >> M)) return 0;

    vector<vector<int>> A(N, vector<int>(N, 0));
    for (int i = 0; i < M; ++i) {
        int u, v;
        cin >> u >> v;
        --u; --v;
        A[u][v] = A[v][u] = 1;
    }

    if (N == 1) {
        cout << 2 % 1000000007 << "\n";
        return 0;
    }

    set<string> valid_trees;

    for (int u = 0; u < N; ++u) {
        for (int v = 0; v < N; ++v) {
            if (u == v) continue;

            vector<int> s(N, 0);
            for (int w = 0; w < N; ++w) {
                if (w == u) continue;
                s[w] = A[u][w] ^ (w == v ? 1 : 0);
            }

            int edges = 0;
            bool possible = true;
            vector<vector<int>> adj(N);

            for (int i = 0; i < N; ++i) {
                for (int j = i + 1; j < N; ++j) {
                    int edge = A[i][j] ^ s[i] ^ s[j];
                    if (edge) {
                        edges++;
                        if (edges > N - 1) {
                            possible = false;
                            break;
                        }
                        adj[i].push_back(j);
                        adj[j].push_back(i);
                    }
                }
                if (!possible) break;
            }

            if (!possible || edges != N - 1) continue;

            vector<bool> vis(N, false);
            vector<int> q;
            q.push_back(0);
            vis[0] = true;
            int head = 0;

            while (head < (int)q.size()) {
                int curr = q[head++];
                for (int nxt : adj[curr]) {
                    if (!vis[nxt]) {
                        vis[nxt] = true;
                        q.push_back(nxt);
                    }
                }
            }

            if (q.size() == N) {
                string tree_str = "";
                for (int i = 0; i < N; ++i) {
                    for (int j = i + 1; j < N; ++j) {
                        tree_str += (A[i][j] ^ s[i] ^ s[j]) ? '1' : '0';
                    }
                }
                valid_trees.insert(tree_str);
            }
        }
    }

    long long ans = valid_trees.size();
    ans = (ans * 2) % 1000000007;
    cout << ans << "\n";

    return 0;
}

