model solution output:
### Main idea

The problem can be modeled as finding an optimal assignment of variables (player positions) to a linear sequence of values ($1$ to $M$) while incurring costs for the choices and distance penalties between certain pairs of variables. This maps perfectly to the Minimum $s-t$ Cut problem.

By defining a large constant `BASE` to convert the maximization of performance into a minimization problem, we construct a directed graph where each player has a chain of nodes. The edges along the chain represent the cost of assigning a player to a specific position. Reverse edges with infinite capacity ensure that exactly one position is chosen per player. Finally, cross-edges between friends' chains accurately accumulate the penalty $C$ for each unit of distance between their chosen positions.

### Technique used

Minimum Cut on a directed network, solved using Dinic's Algorithm for Maximum Flow.

### Correctness argument

For each player $i$, we create a chain of nodes representing prefixes of positions. Cutting the edge between node $j-1$ and $j$ in this chain corresponds to assigning player $i$ to position $j$. The capacity of this edge is set to $\text{BASE} - P_{i,j}$. Infinite capacity reverse edges prevent cutting multiple forward edges, enforcing exactly one position assignment per player.

For every pair of friends $u$ and $v$, and for each position index $j \in [1, M-1]$, we add bidirectional edges of capacity $C$ between their respective chain nodes. If player $u$ is assigned to position $pos_u$ and player $v$ to $pos_v$ (assume $pos_u < pos_v$), then for all $j \in [pos_u, pos_v - 1]$, the node for $v$ will remain in the Source set while the node for $u$ will be in the Sink set. This strictly forces exactly $pos_v - pos_u$ cross-edges of capacity $C$ to be cut, directly modeling the distance penalty $C \times |pos_u - pos_v|$. Subtracting the Minimum Cut value from $N \times \text{BASE}$ yields the exact Maximum Team Performance.

### Complexity analysis

* **Time Complexity:** $\mathcal{O}(V^2 E)$ in the worst case for Dinic's Algorithm. Here, $V = N(M - 1) + 2$ and $E = N \cdot M + N(M - 1) + 2K(M - 1)$. With $N, M, K \le 50$, $V \approx 2500$ and $E \approx 10000$. Because the graph is highly structured and layered (similar to a unit capacity network path), Dinic's operates astronomically faster than its theoretical upper bound and will comfortably run in less than a millisecond, safely passing the 0.5 s time limit.
* **Memory Complexity:** $\mathcal{O}(V + E)$ which is bounded by $\mathcal{O}(N \cdot M + K \cdot M)$. This consumes a fraction of a Megabyte, strictly adhering to the 1024 MB constraint.

### Complete C++20 implementation

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <vector>
#include <queue>
#include <algorithm>

using namespace std;

const long long INF = 1e18;

struct Edge {
    int to;
    long long cap, flow;
    int rev;
};

vector<vector<Edge>> adj;
vector<int> level, ptr;
int S, T;

void add_edge(int from, int to, long long cap) {
    adj[from].push_back({to, cap, 0, (int)adj[to].size()});
    adj[to].push_back({from, 0, 0, (int)adj[from].size() - 1});
}

bool bfs() {
    fill(level.begin(), level.end(), -1);
    level[S] = 0;
    queue<int> q;
    q.push(S);
    while (!q.empty()) {
        int v = q.front();
        q.pop();
        for (const auto& edge : adj[v]) {
            if (edge.cap - edge.flow > 0 && level[edge.to] == -1) {
                level[edge.to] = level[v] + 1;
                q.push(edge.to);
            }
        }
    }
    return level[T] != -1;
}

long long dfs(int v, long long pushed) {
    if (pushed == 0) return 0;
    if (v == T) return pushed;
    for (int& cid = ptr[v]; cid < adj[v].size(); ++cid) {
        auto& edge = adj[v][cid];
        int tr = edge.to;
        if (level[v] + 1 != level[tr] || edge.cap - edge.flow == 0) continue;
        long long push = dfs(tr, min(pushed, edge.cap - edge.flow));
        if (push == 0) continue;
        edge.flow += push;
        adj[tr][edge.rev].flow -= push;
        return push;
    }
    return 0;
}

long long dinic() {
    long long flow = 0;
    while (bfs()) {
        fill(ptr.begin(), ptr.end(), 0);
        while (long long pushed = dfs(S, INF)) {
            flow += pushed;
        }
    }
    return flow;
}

int main() {
    ios_base::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(NULL);

    int n, m, k;
    long long c;
    if (!(cin >> n >> m >> k >> c)) return 0;

    vector<vector<long long>> p(n + 1, vector<long long>(m + 1));
    for (int i = 1; i <= n; ++i) {
        for (int j = 1; j <= m; ++j) {
            cin >> p[i][j];
        }
    }

    S = 0;
    T = n * (m - 1) + 1;
    adj.assign(T + 1, vector<Edge>());
    level.resize(T + 1);
    ptr.resize(T + 1);

    auto idx = [&](int i, int j) {
        return (i - 1) * (m - 1) + j;
    };

    long long BASE = 2000000;

    for (int i = 1; i <= n; ++i) {
        int u_prev = S;
        for (int j = 1; j < m; ++j) {
            int u = idx(i, j);
            add_edge(u_prev, u, BASE - p[i][j]);
            add_edge(u, u_prev, INF);
            u_prev = u;
        }
        add_edge(u_prev, T, BASE - p[i][m]);
    }

    for (int i = 0; i < k; ++i) {
        int u, v;
        cin >> u >> v;
        for (int j = 1; j < m; ++j) {
            int node_u = idx(u, j);
            int node_v = idx(v, j);
            add_edge(node_u, node_v, c);
            add_edge(node_v, node_u, c);
        }
    }

    long long max_flow = dinic();
    long long ans = (long long)n * BASE - max_flow;

    cout << ans << "\n";

    return 0;
}

```

