model solution output:
### Main idea

The problem asks us to determine if we can partition $P$ players into at most two groups such that each player has an odd number of friends in their own group. We can model this as an assignment of binary variables $x_i \in \{0, 1\}$ representing the group of player $i$.

Let $d_i$ be the degree of player $i$, and let $c_1$ be the number of their friends placed in group 1. We can write the condition algebraically for each player $i$:

* If $x_i = 0$, we need the number of friends in group 0 (which is $d_i - c_1$) to be odd. So, $d_i - c_1 \equiv 1 \pmod 2 \implies c_1 \equiv d_i + 1 \pmod 2$.
* If $x_i = 1$, we need the number of friends in group 1 (which is $c_1$) to be odd. So, $c_1 \equiv 1 \pmod 2$.

Both scenarios naturally unify into a single linear equation over GF(2):


$$(d_i \pmod 2) x_i + \sum_{j \in N(i)} x_j \equiv (d_i + 1) \pmod 2$$

Thus, the entire graph can be represented as a system of $P$ linear equations with $P$ variables modulo 2.

### Technique used

Gaussian elimination over the finite field GF(2).

### Correctness argument

Because the conditions for a valid match-making partition directly translate to a system of linear equations over GF(2), the problem strictly reduces to checking the satisfiability of this system. Gaussian elimination finds a solution to a system of linear equations or correctly identifies if it is inconsistent. By transforming the augmented matrix of this system into reduced row echelon form, we simply check for any row that evaluates to $0 = 1$. If such a row exists, the partition is impossible; otherwise, at least one valid partition is guaranteed to exist.

### Complexity analysis

* **Time Complexity:** $\mathcal{O}(P^3)$. The Gaussian elimination is performed on a $P \times (P+1)$ augmented matrix. Since $2 \le P \le 100$ , $P^3 = 10^6$ operations, which is extremely fast and comfortably runs within the 0.25 seconds time limit.


* **Memory Complexity:** $\mathcal{O}(P^2)$. We need an adjacency matrix and a 2D array for the system of equations. For $P \le 100$, this takes a negligible amount of space, well within the generous 1024 megabytes limit.



### Complete C++20 implementation

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <vector>
#include <utility>

using namespace std;

int main() {
    ios_base::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(NULL);

    int P, F;
    if (!(cin >> P >> F)) return 0;

    vector<vector<int>> adj(P, vector<int>(P, 0));
    vector<int> deg(P, 0);

    for (int i = 0; i < F; ++i) {
        int u, v;
        cin >> u >> v;
        --u; --v;
        adj[u][v] = 1;
        adj[v][u] = 1;
        deg[u]++;
        deg[v]++;
    }

    vector<vector<int>> mat(P, vector<int>(P + 1, 0));
    for (int i = 0; i < P; ++i) {
        mat[i][i] = deg[i] % 2;
        mat[i][P] = (deg[i] + 1) % 2;
        for (int j = 0; j < P; ++j) {
            if (i != j && adj[i][j]) {
                mat[i][j] = 1;
            }
        }
    }

    int r = 0;
    for (int c = 0; c < P && r < P; ++c) {
        int pivot = r;
        while (pivot < P && mat[pivot][c] == 0) pivot++;
        if (pivot == P) continue;

        swap(mat[r], mat[pivot]);

        for (int i = 0; i < P; ++i) {
            if (i != r && mat[i][c]) {
                for (int j = c; j <= P; ++j) {
                    mat[i][j] ^= mat[r][j];
                }
            }
        }
        r++;
    }

    bool possible = true;
    for (int i = 0; i < P; ++i) {
        bool all_zero = true;
        for (int j = 0; j < P; ++j) {
            if (mat[i][j]) {
                all_zero = false;
                break;
            }
        }
        if (all_zero && mat[i][P]) {
            possible = false;
            break;
        }
    }

    if (possible) {
        cout << "Y\n";
    } else {
        cout << "N\n";
    }

    return 0;
}

